WEBVTT

00:01.904 --> 00:08.014
This is Mary Lee Nolan in an interview with Mrs. 
Lupe Alemán. What's

00:08.034 --> 00:14.786
her name? Guadalupe Alemán, but Lupe, well, 
Grande is Guadalupe Alemán. And for my father,

00:24.854 --> 00:26.577
González. González. Yes. Lupe González de 
Alemán. Yes, for my husband. Yes. And where were

00:34.769 --> 00:36.492
you born? I was born here in the Nueces County. Yes. 
Yes, I was born here, I was raised here. In what

00:47.509 --> 00:48.891
year? Well, I think I was 17, it seems. And where was 
your father born? My father, well, they are both

00:54.115 --> 00:57.960
from Mexico. But I don't know where they are from. 
No? No. But they invented a lot of... Nanahuato.

01:11.618 --> 01:12.499
Nanahuato? Yes. Rial del Oro, Rial de Pozos. I 
think they are neighbors like Tricorpos. Yes. And

01:21.911 --> 01:23.093
Robstown. And that's what I heard them talking 
about. Yes. And I was born...

01:34.335 --> 01:39.423
I was the first girl, I think, in their family. 
Because I grew up in a place where they worked all

01:40.204 --> 01:48.939
day. They worked. My father, my grandparents, 
they worked all those lands because it was

01:51.811 --> 02:04.204
just a mountain. And they dug a lot with talaches 
and with that they kept us, all of us, they kept

02:04.224 --> 02:17.599
digging, digging and de-rooting. Todos mis tios, 
mis abuelitos, mi papá, And my brother, the one I

02:26.219 --> 02:31.144
have there, I have a brother who lives there in the 
corner. And that brother helped my father because

02:32.265 --> 02:35.889
he was the oldest. But they were born in Mexico, the 
two of them. They just came here, they were raised

02:38.832 --> 02:42.416
here. And he was the oldest and he helped my father. 
To grab the talacha, to dig very hard. He worked

02:47.802 --> 02:53.728
very hard, my little brother and my father, to 
raise the others. Well, and then that I know from

02:55.244 --> 03:07.575
those times that I grew up, that I was knowing, I 
still recognized all that. I

03:07.995 --> 03:15.542
went to where my father worked. I looked at them as 
they worked very hard. And then I looked at many

03:20.987 --> 03:25.251
fields and many people. their clothes hanging on 
the branches, their, this, grinding, making

03:26.598 --> 03:52.420
tortillas, some big firewood, there they put a 
comal like this, they were throwing tortillas,

03:26.598 --> 03:52.420
tortillas, and making their food, well. I met a lot 
of friends like that. So, I would look at what my

03:56.539 --> 04:01.227
grandpa was doing. What is grandpa doing? He would 
say, I am making, they were called, those were

04:03.691 --> 04:10.543
called galemes. Galemes? Galemes, from pure 
land. From pure land, they made from firewood,

04:15.050 --> 04:19.278
from the inside, from pure firewood. And then, 
They would put them like this. Then they would put

04:23.110 --> 04:26.314
grass on the firewood. Then they would put a lot of 
dirt on top of everything. They would cover it with

04:29.818 --> 04:31.480
dirt. That whole pile of dirt. But the firewood 
would stay inside. And then there would be a hole in

04:35.104 --> 04:39.649
the firewood. And they would put a lot of firewood 
in there. And a lot of garbage so that a lot of

04:42.492 --> 04:46.057
firewood would be made. That would burn. It would 
burn. After it burned, I think it lasted, I don't

04:48.914 --> 04:59.528
know much, but it seemed to last three days or a week 
to cook. It was coal, like the one they make now.

05:03.573 --> 05:15.128
Well, then, after it was ready, he was paying, 
paying, and he was getting smaller and smaller.

05:15.148 --> 05:16.710
So, with a rake, they were doing it. And they did it, 
and they did it, and they dug around it, and they

05:17.770 --> 05:28.267
were stretching it with that rake when it was 
already turned off. So, here they had it very

05:29.269 --> 05:39.205
clean, and they were making all that coal like 
this, it had already been done, they did it like

05:29.269 --> 05:39.205
this, like this, all around they dug it with that 
rake. That coal, there were many ribbons, you know

05:40.282 --> 05:45.347
what ribbons are. Well, then they threw all that 
coal, they picked it like a potato. They picked

05:51.773 --> 05:54.996
that coal, they ribbons, the ribbons like that. 
They carried 30, 40 ribbons of that, of pure coal.

06:00.742 --> 06:06.187
The town was very small, the town was very small. 
What was this town called? This little town? Yes.

06:11.782 --> 06:26.518
Well, from what I know, I don't know, but I never 
knew, since I knew what it was called, it was

06:11.782 --> 06:26.518
Corpos, because they took it to Corpos, when there 
were very few shops. My grandpa took it to a huayín

06:27.780 --> 06:33.646
and there were no mules, because those, I think, 
cost more. He had some burritos, sí, sí, y él

06:35.682 --> 06:43.873
llevaba todos esos costalitos en eso y los llevaba 
a corpos. Entonces mi abuelito no quería, mi

06:43.893 --> 06:53.405
abuelito no quería hablar, él le daba vergüenza, 
pero mi abuelita sí iba con él. Mi abuelita era una

06:54.346 --> 06:58.011
señora muy delgadita, She was a very pretty lady, 
but she was dark-skinned. But she had a very pretty

07:04.175 --> 07:09.121
body. She would go out on the street and say, Do you 
buy coal? Yes, the ladies would come out. Good

07:23.498 --> 07:24.379
morning. Good morning. This is my mother. Nice to 
meet you. Oh, here. Here, here. And then she tells

07:35.574 --> 07:41.143
me, well... So, when she talked about all that, the 
ladies and gentlemen would go out to buy my

07:41.164 --> 07:51.522
grandparents. I don't know if at that time it would 
cost about 15 cents, I think a dime. They were very

07:59.618 --> 08:03.125
happy. So with that, they bought everything they 
needed for food. They bought everything they

08:10.908 --> 08:27.245
needed from the food, they came very delighted to 
the house because they brought a lot of food, of

08:10.908 --> 08:27.245
what they wanted with that. Well, they followed 
them around, around with that. Well, following

08:31.189 --> 08:39.177
until they finished that, but they always 
continued to dig, to dig, because they were paid

08:31.189 --> 08:39.177
money for that. An acre, half an acre, they paid for 
it. A fourth, an eighth, they said, that's what

08:43.042 --> 08:48.209
they paid for, what they did. A little, but they 
paid for it. Well, then, that was over and Desenray

08:50.853 --> 08:56.801
continued.

