24:21.819 --> 24:26.725
were paid for that pasture, because they carried 
all that pasture to the machine. He had a machine

24:27.627 --> 24:33.514
that you put the manhojo there, they were pure 
manhojos. They cut it in the work and then they put

24:33.534 --> 24:39.743
it in the barn. You see, they were in the barn. He put 
workers to make the barn, like the Indians, that's

24:41.164 --> 24:46.131
how they did it. Well, then, here were some 
loaders, the guayines arrived, like trunks, and

24:46.111 --> 25:03.127
they threw those loaders, they threw the pasture, 
the guayines, and they put them so high, so high,

24:46.111 --> 25:03.127
that's how they carried the guayines, all out of 
order, to the silos, to the machine. Then, there,

25:03.647 --> 25:13.857
the guayine was like this, throwing all that 
manure there, and the machine was stirring it, and

25:03.647 --> 25:13.857
throwing it into that boat. I think my father was 
paid, I'm not very sure because he didn't tell us,

25:14.461 --> 25:29.297
but I think he was paid like 5 or 10 pesos a day on each 
trip. On each trip he was paid. So he was earning his

25:34.162 --> 25:42.932
money and it was less for him. They ran the guayines 
in a row, like trunks. The first one to arrive would

25:50.401 --> 25:56.792
be the one to be loaded first, and the other one 
would make more trips. Well, then my father with

25:56.812 --> 26:01.561
that guayín maintained the house much better. But 
between the family and my mother, she... and she

26:10.486 --> 26:16.312
would tell my father to buy what he needed all the 
time. She didn't want good clothes, she didn't

26:16.352 --> 26:23.399
want anything good, like now. She wanted my father 
to have what he needed to work. That's what she said

26:27.584 --> 26:30.767
too. So, he, my father, for a long time, he changed 
from there. And then she gave it to me because I

26:39.173 --> 26:46.385
think time was over. So my grandparents, they were 
